Czech Republic has a chance to raise 365 billion
Czech government ministers signed a total of nine operational programmes with representatives of the European Commission yesterday, of which the Czech Republic can receive 14 billion euros (approximately 365 billion crowns) in the coming years.
It is about half of the total amount that the Czech Republic can receive from Brussels between 2007 and 2013.
Approximately CZK 125 billion will go from seven operational programmes to the regions.
Czech companies will be able to receive around 100 billion crowns from the Enterprise and Innovation Programme.
Most of the money, up to $150 billion, will go to transport.
The Transport Programme is the largest operational programme and represents up to 22 percent of the funds that the Czech Republic can receive from the funds.
This money will be increased by the budget of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure, which will manage CZK 90.8 billion next year.
The Enterprise and Innovation Programme is intended to be used by entrepreneurs and companies to raise funds for innovative entrepreneurship.
Companies should raise funding for the introduction of new technologies, for industrial research, but also for the implementation of more effective organisational methods.
In the current drawdown of money from EU funds, the Czech Republic is still among the least successful in the newly adopted countries.
